    "question_id" : 6458657,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>System.out.println is a PrintStream, which <a href=\"http://download.oracle.com/javase/6/docs/api/java/io/PrintStream.html#println%28%29\" rel=\"nofollow\">uses the environment setting</a> for <a href=\"http://download.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/essential/environment/sysprop.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">line.separator</a> as its, well, line separator.  One solution to your problem would be to pass in -Dline.separator argument.</p>\n\n<p>Probably the best solution though is to just use view your file with a better editor.  Notepad++ and many others on Windows will understand both types of line endings, while notepad will not.  Even the builtin wordpad does a better job of displaying unix file endings.</p>\n"
  }, {
